<HEAD>Retired Federal Judge Dead at 80</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired U.S. District Judge Owen D.
Cox, who in the 1970s ordered the busing of thousands of students
in the interest of desegregation, has died after a long illness. He
was 80.
   Cox died at a nursing home Saturday night.
   A longtime local attorney and prominent member of the Republican
Party, Cox was appointed to the federal bench in 1970 by President
Nixon.
   Cases he handled during his 10 years on the bench included a
desegregation lawsuit against the Corpus Christi Independent School
District. In the 1970s, he ordered the busing of thousands of
students.
   Cox was an assistant Texas attorney general in 1942 and Corpus
Christi city attorney from 1943 to 1947, except for 20 months of
military service during World War II.
   Survivors include two daughters, a son and three grandchildren.
   Funeral arrangements were pending.
</TEXT>
